			    "content": "Classical Chinese is the written language used for writing and communication in ancient China, formed and developed on the basis of the spoken language of the pre-Qin period, with a history of several thousand years. Unlike modern vernacular Chinese, Classical Chinese emphasizes conciseness and precise wording, often using very few characters to express rich meanings. For example, the eight characters \"学而时习之，不亦说乎\" encompass the method and attitude of learning, as well as the inner feeling of joy, while expressing the same idea in vernacular would require many more words. Classical Chinese has its own system of grammar, vocabulary, and function words, commonly including modal particles like \"之, 乎, 者, 也, 矣, 焉\" and special sentence patterns such as causative and purposive constructions, which give it a unique rhythm and prosodic beauty. From pre-Qin philosophical texts like the Analects and Mencius, to dynastic histories like the Records of the Grand Historian and the Book of Han, and then to Tang poetry, Song lyrics, Yuan opera, and Ming and Qing dynasty novels, Classical Chinese has carried the thoughts, history, literature, and wisdom of the Chinese nation for thousands of years. Learning Classical Chinese is like opening a door to the treasure house of ancient culture; we can directly read original texts and engage in cross-temporal dialogues with sages such as Confucius, Sima Qian, Li Bai, and Su Shi. Although vernacular became mainstream in modern times for the sake of mass education and daily communication, Classical Chinese has never disappeared. Many of its vocabulary, allusions, and expressions have long been deeply integrated into modern Chinese. For example, idioms like \"suddenly see the light\" (恍然大悟), \"the road is long and the burden is heavy\" (任重道远), and \"blow hot and cold\" (朝三暮四) all originate from Classical Chinese. Today, we learn Classical Chinese not only to read ancient texts and pass exams but also to inherit cultural roots, cultivate an elegant linguistic taste, and draw wisdom from the ancients on how to conduct ourselves and face life's challenges with courage."
