			    "id": "chi_021",
			    "title": "Instant Noodles",
			    "content": "Instant noodles, fully known as convenience noodles, are a type of fast food born in the modern fast-paced lifestyle that quickly became popular worldwide. The core process involves taking cooked noodles and subjecting them to steaming and frying (or hot-air drying), reducing the moisture content to an extremely low level so they can be stored for a long time without spoiling. To eat, one simply adds boiling water and waits three to five minutes; the noodles rehydrate and soften, and together with the accompanying sauce and seasoning packets, form a steaming hot, fragrant bowl of noodles. The inventor of instant noodles was the Japanese-Taiwanese businessman Momofuku Ando, who introduced the world's first \"Chicken Ramen\" in 1958, completely changing people's perception of \"cooking.\" Since then, instant noodles have continuously evolved, developing various packaging forms such as bagged, bowl, and cup noodles. Flavors have also diversified from the original light chicken broth to hundreds or even thousands of varieties, including braised beef, shrimp, pickled cabbage, spicy beef, Tom Yum Kung, and curry. Almost every country and region has its unique instant noodle flavor. The greatest charm of instant noodles lies in their convenience, low cost, and delicious taste. For students and office workers staying up late, they are the warmest comfort in the dead of night; for long-distance travelers, they are a familiar taste on the train; in outdoor adventures or emergency relief situations, they provide the fastest and most effective food source. However, instant noodles have long been associated with debates about being \"unhealthy,\" due to high salt, high oil, high calories, and a lack of nutrients like protein and dietary fiber. In fact, the modern food industry has made many improvements, such as using non-fried noodle cakes, reducing sodium content, and adding freeze-dried vegetable packets. More importantly, clever eaters have invented various \"upgraded ways to eat them\": adding eggs, vegetables, ham slices, cheese slices, or even tomatoes and fatty beef while cooking the noodles can turn a simple bowl of instant noodles into a nutritionally balanced and hearty meal. Instant noodles are not just a food; they are also a cultural symbol, representing modern people's pursuit of both efficiency and flavor, and carrying countless memories of struggle, loneliness, companionship, and youth."
